text: Tom we don't know the outcome yet in
Iraq and may not for a couple more days
but nonetheless the US commander the top
US commander in Iraq Ray Odierno said on
Monday morning that the u.s. is on track
to leave and turn over control to the
Iraqi security forces now my question
for you is how can he be so sure of that
at this point is he really right I think
his initial assessment was based on the
fact that while there was certainly
significant amounts of violence over the
weekend and on Election Day yesterday
over all that violence did not impact
the voting or the turnout the voting
actually as a percentage of registered
voters was higher than national
elections a year ago although a little
lower than the last time in 2005 I spoke
with general Odierno when he was in town
just a couple of weeks ago briefing the
defense secretary the chairman of the
Joint Chiefs and the President on his
plans at the time Jane he told me that
he would take 30 60 or 90 days to fully
be able to decide on the pace of the
future drawdown plan but I think what we
heard him say this morning is that thus
far at least things are going no it does
seem and again it's early but it's but
it's possible that Prime Minister Nouri
Kamal al-maliki won't win a clear
victory here even if he wins at all so
how has that changed the calculation if
he some his son some sort of a
power-sharing arrangement right I think
from general Odierno standpoint he's not
going to ignore the politics but he's
looking at the security situation so in
and of itself negotiations on a
coalition government don't necessarily
mean the troop withdrawal would have to
slow down if they proceeded calmly and
there's of course many examples where
coalition negotiations do go smoothly
although there's plenty of examples in
the region where they don't what kind of
a sense do us commanders get from the
overall security situation from the
bombings that we saw on Sunday as the
election began I think really how you
view the security situation on Election
Day is sort of a Rorschach test for how
you view the
mission if you want to see the mission
going badly you can point to a very
large car bomb in naija you can point to
the mortar fire the rocket fire the
number of bottle bombs that were thrown
around Baghdad the fact that almost 40
people were killed in Baghdad from that
standpoint you can say there was a lot
of violence but those who want to see
this as more of a success the glass half
full crowd will say look there were
5,000 polling places across the country
it's a large country many millions of
people turned out to vote and it was a
larger percentage than voted a year ago
so they will view that as a success
despite the violence my last question
for you just quickly and I don't know if
there is a quick answer but are the
Iraqi security forces ready or will they
be by the time the US begins to pull out
it's a rolling readiness at the small
unit tactical level Jane I think they're
ready to patrol and control small areas
but at a national level they are not
ready yet but August when the combat
troops come out in 2011 when the rest of
the US US troops come out that's really
a long ways off as always thanks so much
Thank You Jane
